<section xml:id="s_derivative_at_point">
  <title>Derivative at a point</title>


<definition xml:id="d_derivative_at_point">
  <title>Derivative at an interior point</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f</m>  be a real-valued function with domain <m>D\subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>c</m> be an interior point of <m>D</m>. The function <m>f</m> is <term>differentiable at <m>c</m></term> if
      <me>
      \lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}
      </me>
      exists. When this is the case, we call the limit the <term>derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>c</m></term>, denoted <m>f'(c)</m>: <ie />,
      <me>
        f'(c)=\lim_{x\to c}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}
      </me>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>


<definition xml:id="d_lrderivative">
  <title>Left and right derivatives</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f</m>  be a real-valued function with domain <m>D\subseteq \mathbb{R}</m>.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <title>Left derivative at a point</title>
        <p> Let <m>c\in D</m>, and suppose <m>D</m> contains an interval of the form <m>(b,c]</m>. We say <m>f</m> is <term>left-differentiable at <m>c</m></term> if
        <me>
        \lim_{x\to c^-}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}
        </me>
         exists. When this is the case, we call the limit the <term>left derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>c</m></term>.
       </p>
      </li>
      <li>
        <title> Right derivative at a point</title>
        <p> Let <m>c\in D</m>, and suppose <m>D</m> contains an interval of the form <m>[c,d)</m>. We say <m>f</m> is <term>right-differentiable at <m>c</m></term> if
        <me>
        \lim_{x\to c^+}\frac{f(x)-f(c)}{x-c}
        </me>
         exists. When this is the case, we call the limit the <term>right  derivative of <m>f</m> at <m>c</m></term>.
       </p>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </statement>
</definition>


</section>
